SIMPLE: excision
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Excision
<hw>Ex*ci"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>excisio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>excision</ets>. See
<er>Excide</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of excising or cutting
out or off; extirpation; destruction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such conquerors are the instruments of vengeance on those nations
that have . . . grown ripe for <qex>excision</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>The act of cutting off from the
church; excommunication.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>The removal, especially of small
parts, with a cutting instrument.</def> <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Excitability</ent>⟦br⟧
